{"author":{"id":"458c2786e2fb21c7f2463be283bdb1d457c6c22ed9854985782318ab918e2e3f"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1460042197,"nonce":"Ke3szdkGwNexh60S3ipBzKIA6W0=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDIwNjk0OTE2OQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/716#issuecomment-206949169"},"message":"@bgruening First off, I want to say that I completely understand the value of the `depot` in terms of practicality and making things \"just work\". For that reason, I think it's likely worth the tradeoffs. However, I do think there are tradeoffs in complexity (it's at least a mirror and point of failure), and in transparency.\n\nI have a few issues that I'd like to see addressed (and I'd be willing to help where I can).\n1. When I look at a tool in the toolshed, I see that it's downloading some tarball from `depot`. I can't (easily) determine what that code is, where it came from, how it was generated, etc. In this instance, I had no way of knowing it was an unmodified tarball from bioconductor. (Is that even correct?)\n2. In addition to not really know what the code is, I have no simple way to contribute updates or fixes to it. This is a piece that is potentially separate from either the tool in the toolshed or the upstream tool itself. BTW, in this case, I think I'd have a preference to keep the Galaxy specific code in the Galaxy toolshed repository and not a separate (third) repo.\n3. My Galaxy installation is now dependent on the `depot` being up and maintained by the Galaxy team. While this is a nice service, it's an added level of dependency that wasn't there when the recipes simply got the source code directly from the upstream project.\n\nI do believe that documentation could go a long way to mitigating these issues. Perhaps adding information to the wiki as well as a landing page on https://depot.galaxyproject.org/ that helps people to understand what is there and how it was generated.\n\nIn short, I very much appreciate everyone's efforts and I do think things are getting more reliable, but from my perspective they are getting increasingly complex and the documentation of how things work, how things are changing, and where things are going is lacking. For example, conda, docker, depot, and starforge are all things I've heard of, but don't fully grasp how the Galaxy Project is using them.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1460042257,"nonce":"Ec/AUla7MVera3ZT9Z6sTo3Uudc=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDIwNjk0OTUzOA==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/716#issuecomment-206949538"},"message":"@bgruening Oh, and as far as the DESeq2 help section, I'm happy to help, but first I need to sort out what it's actually doing. I still am not quite sure (bit of code to dig through) ;-)","files":null}]}